<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06191171 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06191171 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  TREE; INDUSTRY; MEETING; SANTA-CRUZ  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The state Board of Forestry is holding a public hearing tonight in Santa Cruzto hear complaints and concerns about logging in central and NorthernCalifornia.;    It is the seventh and final public workshop to be held in thestate this summer. The workshops were designed to allow the public,particularly people whose property borders private logging operations, tovoice concerns about the effect logging has on their watershed, and suggestways to resolve any problems.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  HEARING TO ADDRESS LOGGINGSTATE BOARD SEEKING COMMUNITY'S IDEAS  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     'Pretty poor reputation';  &quot;They've (Board of Forestry members) got apretty poor reputation with the public and they're kind of tired of gettingbeat up on,&quot; said Al Haynes, San Lorenzo Valley Water District watershedmanager, who will chair the meeting. &quot;They're trying to get out in front ofthe curve, so to speak, by getting people who are familiar with the rules tocome out and tell them how the rules are working.&quot;;    The board also wants toknow what the public feels must be done to maintain a successful monitoringprogram, he said.;    Haynes, one of 20 advisers evaluating state forestrymanagement practices and regulations for the Board of Forestry, is to bejoined by at least four other advisers.;    The advisory panel includesregistered foresters, water department employees from districts throughoutCalifornia, aquatic biologists, environmentalists and private citizens.;   Recommendations next month;  Haynes will make recommendations to the Board ofForestry next month based on issues raised at the meeting. He said he willreport on how people in the affected communities see the results of logging onstreams and other water resources, and how those results should be measured todetermine whether they are in line with state and federal water pollutioncontrol rules.; IFYOU'RE INTERESTED; The hearing will be at 7 p.m. in theSanta Cruz County Board of Supervisors chambers on the fifth floor of thecounty building at 701 Ocean St.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  TERRI MORGAN, Special to the Mercury News  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Santa Cruz/Monterey  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910709  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  July  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  313  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday July 9, 199100191171,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>